{"outcome":{"note":{}},"ticketId":"58","phase":"product","id":"58-71","detail":"---\n\n## Product-phase report for #58: `truncateWords` in text-utilities\n\n### 1. Module location & stack\n\n| Fact | Detail |\n|---|---|\n| **Module path** | `apps\/web\/src\/lib\/text-utilities\/` |\n| **Language** | TypeScript |\n| **Test framework** | Vitest (config at `apps\/web\/vitest.config.ts`, includes `src\/**\/*.test.ts`) |\n| **Package** | `@vokda\/web` — SvelteKit app (`apps\/web\/package.json`) |\n| **Test command** | `npm run test` (aliased from root: `just test`) |\n\n### 2. Existing tokenization (the splitter to reuse)\n\nThe single tokenizer for the whole module is `normalizeText` at `normalize-text.ts:43`:\n\n```ts\nexport function normalizeText(text: string): string {\n  const collapsed = text.replace(\/\\s+\/g, ' ').trim();\n  return collapsed;\n}\n```\n\nIt collapses all whitespace runs (`\/\\s+\/g`) to a single space, trims, and returns `\"\"` for empty\/whitespace-only input. Both `wordCount` and `truncateWords` already compose on it.\n\n### 3. Existing `wordCount`\n\nAt `word-count.ts:26`:\n\n```ts\nexport function wordCount(text: string): number {\n  const normalised = normalizeText(text);\n  if (normalised === '') return 0;\n  return normalised.split(' ').length;\n}\n```\n\n### 4. `truncateWords` — **already implemented**\n\nThe function **already exists** at `truncate-words.ts:44` and is **exported** from `index.ts:3`. Signature:\n\n```ts\nexport function truncateWords(text: string, maxWords: number): string\n```\n\nIt uses `normalizeText` (the same tokenizer), so it satisfies the \"reuse existing tokenization\" requirement. Full JSDoc with examples is present.\n\n### 5. Acceptance criteria — all met by existing code\n\n| Criterion | Status | Evidence |\n|---|---|---|\n| Export from text-utilities module | ✅ | `index.ts:3` — `export { truncateWords } from '.\/truncate-words'` |\n| `<= maxWords` → unchanged, no ellipsis | ✅ | `truncate-words.ts:48` — `if (words.length <= maxWords) return normalised;` |\n| `> maxWords` → first N words + `…` | ✅ | `truncate-words.ts:49` — `return words.slice(0, maxWords).join(' ') + '…';` |\n| `maxWords <= 0` → `\"\"` | ✅ | `truncate-words.ts:45` — `if (maxWords <= 0) return '';` (handles `-Infinity` too) |\n| Empty\/whitespace → `\"\"` | ✅ | `truncate-words.ts:46-47` — `const normalised = normalizeText(text); if (normalised === '') return '';` |\n| Reuses existing tokenization | ✅ | Calls `normalizeText` from `normalize-text.ts` — same splitter as `wordCount` |\n\n### 6. Tests — already written and comprehensive\n\n`index.test.ts` has a dedicated `describe('truncateWords', ...)` block (lines 82–150) with 12 test cases covering:\n\n- `maxWords = 0` \/ `-1` \/ `-Infinity`\n- Empty string and whitespace-only input\n- Fewer words than max (no ellipsis), including leading\/trailing whitespace\n- Exactly maxWords (no ellipsis), including leading\/trailing whitespace\n- More words than max (ellipsis appended), including leading\/trailing whitespace\n- Single-word truncation to 1 word\n- Many extra whitespace characters\n\n### 7. Summary\n\n**This work item is already complete.** The `truncateWords` function exists with the exact signature, behavior, and tests the issue requests. It composes on `normalizeText` — the same tokenizer used by `wordCount`. All acceptance criteria are satisfied by the current code. No new code is needed.","at":804617691.53845}
